{"candidates": [{"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency iff e in (1/(k+1), k/(k+2)) AND p > p_min(e,r,k) := e*(k-1)/(k+1) / [e*(k-1)/(k+1) + (1-e)*r*(k+1)/(k-1)], with critic recall r in (0,1); the loss regime is p < p_min where false flags on correct answers exceed saved votes.\", \"mechanism\": \"Binomial majority-vote model: SC correctness is P[Bin(k,1-e)>k/2]; harness adds a filtering layer that removes TPs (bad candidates, prob r*e) and FPs (good candidates, prob (1-p)(1-e)). Net benefit requires FP removal rate < TP removal rate scaled by majority-margin. Differentiating shows the break-even precision p_min collapses to 0 as e approaches 1/(k+1) or k/(k+2), is maximized at the midpoint, and the window is nonempty for odd k>=5. Fixed-precision critics operating outside this window yield zero net benefit, explaining the repository's null results (e=0.033, 0.01 both far below the k=5 window of (0.167, 0.714)).\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k>=5\", \"base error 1/(k+1) < e < k/(k+2)\", \"critic precision p > p_min(e,r,k) for given recall r\", \"independent critic whose FP and TP rates are not question-adaptive\"], \"excludes\": [\"even k (tie-breaking complications)\", \"critic that adapts confidence per-question\", \"k<5 (majority too thin for robust filtering signal)\", \"e outside the fragility window\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment produces e_hat within (0.17, 0.71) with p_hat > p_min(r_hat) but harness accuracy <= SC accuracy\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment produces p_hat < p_min(r_hat) yet harness accuracy strictly exceeds SC accuracy\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Observed FP-removal rate on correct-majority questions exceeds 50% of observed TP-removal rate while harness still beats SC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Unifies 7811dbda and e977c688 by deriving the full 3D boundary surface p_min(e,r,k). The decisive experiment must scan both e and critic-threshold to hit the interior of the fragility window. Predicted p_min is lowest near window edges (easy to beat) and highest at the center (hardest to beat), so a threshold sweep is essential to find regions where available critic p exceeds p_min.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "e977c688ba005d3f8e9136e93656d8b5e72254470555b462a5c80e2954808770"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}], "typicality": 0.78}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"No single fixed (p, r) regime suffices; harness strictly beats SC only when critic operating point is question-adaptive: critic confidence c(q) is high on questions with fragile majorities (margin <= 1) and low on questions with robust majorities, so that filtering concentrates TPs where they matter and avoids FPs where they don't.\", \"mechanism\": \"Critics with fixed thresholds face an inevitable precision-recall tradeoff: any threshold aggressive enough to catch marginal-bad candidates also flags marginal-good candidates. On robust-majority questions, these FPs are pure loss (SC already correct, filtering can only break). On fragile-majority questions, TPs are high-value (can flip a 3-2 wrong to 2-2 tie or 3-2 right to 2-3). An adaptive critic that raises its threshold on robust-majority questions and lowers it on fragile ones shifts operating point per-question, achieving p(q), r(q) that clear p_min on fragile questions while avoiding FPs on robust ones. Repository nulls are explained: the critic operated at a fixed threshold, and all questions were either ceiling (robust majority) or too easy, so the adaptive mechanism never engaged.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k>=5 any parity\", \"question-adaptive critic threshold c(q)\", \"mixed-difficulty item sets where some questions have fragile majorities\", \"critic with access to candidate-similarity or margin signals\"], \"excludes\": [\"fixed-threshold critics (cannot escape the precision-recall tradeoff across all question types)\", \"uniform-difficulty sets where all questions have the same majority margin\", \"critic without any signal to adapt on (no margin, no similarity, no confidence)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Adaptive-critic harness accuracy <= fixed-threshold harness accuracy on a set containing >= 30% fragile-majority questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Critic confidence c(q) shows no correlation with majority-margin (|rho| < 0.15) yet adaptive harness beats SC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"FP rate on robust-majority questions under adaptive threshold exceeds FP rate under fixed threshold\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Directly extends 30e483eb and negates 559750's base-case. The decisive experiment must induce fragile majorities AND give the critic a margin/similarity signal to adapt on, then compare adaptive vs fixed-threshold filtering. Budget allocation: ~120k tokens for hard-set generation (difficult items targeting e~0.3-0.5 at k=5), ~30k for candidate pool generation, ~30k for adaptive critic (prompted with margin signal), ~30k for fixed-threshold critic, ~90k for evaluation across 3 arms.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}, {"role": "dependence", "target": "5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"}], "typicality": 0.62}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats SC iff the joint distribution of candidate errors and critic flags has higher mutual information between 'bad candidate' and 'critic flag' than between 'majority is wrong' and 'critic flags anything', i.e., I(C;B) > I(C;M_wrong) where C=flag pattern, B=per-candidate badness, M_wrong=majority error. This collapses to the fixed-regime window only under independence assumptions that real critics violate.\", \"mechanism\": \"Redefine the problem in information-theoretic terms: harness transforms the candidate pool by removing flagged candidates, changing the majority-vote input distribution. The benefit is a function of how much the flag pattern tells us about individual badness vs. how much it merely correlates with aggregate majority error. If the critic flags are correlated with majority-wrongness but not with individual badness (e.g., critic flags all candidates on hard questions), it has high I(C;M_wrong) but low I(C;B), and filtering merely removes random candidates from wrong-majority questions without fixing them. If flags are per-candidate-informative (high I(C;B)), filtering selectively removes bad candidates and can flip fragile wrong majorities. The fragility window and p_min threshold are special cases under the assumption that critic flags are conditionally independent given candidate quality.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"any k>=3\", \"critics with arbitrary flag-dependence structure\", \"both fixed and adaptive critic thresholds\", \"sets where critic flags may correlate with question difficulty\"], \"excludes\": [\"critic flags that are deterministic functions of candidate quality (trivial case, I(C;B)=H(B), harness always wins)\", \"k=1 (no majority to filter)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"I(C;B) > I(C;M_wrong) measured empirically but harness accuracy <= SC accuracy\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"I(C;B) <= I(C;M_wrong) but harness accuracy strictly exceeds SC accuracy\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Per-candidate flag accuracy > 0.6 but mutual information I(C;B) < I(C;M_wrong) and harness still beats SC\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Atypical because it reframes the precision/recall regime as an information-theoretic inequality rather than a threshold condition. The experiment must measure both mutual informations empirically: generate pools, collect critic flags, compute I(C;B) from per-candidate flag-vs-truth tables and I(C;M_wrong) from flag-pattern-vs-majority-error tables, then test whether the inequality predicts harness>SC. Budget: ~100k for hard-set generation, ~40k for candidate pools, ~40k for critic flags, ~30k for MI estimation and evaluation. If the inequality is violated but harness still wins, the information-theoretic framing is refuted in favor of the threshold model.\"}", "refs": [{"role": "dependence", "target": "324c6fa9540384cf3fc3f2e3aa2a22bf6716654413b5a55a0c38f37ce7883040"}, {"role": "mention", "target": "7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}], "typicality": 0.25}]}